    "narrative": "The **Zurich Zebras** face a complex slate today, headlined by the elite efficiency score of **Yordan Alvarez** (77.33), who remains a must-start despite a neutral park factor against Andre Pallante. **Yordan Alvarez** benefits from strong lineup protection and a +11% boost from the matchup\u2019s SP skill profile. Meanwhile, **Hyeseong Kim** (70.16) and **Colt Keith** (68.51) emerge as the primary engines for our Roto categories; **Hyeseong Kim** is particularly valuable today, as the matchup against a slower-delivering starter offers a 100% stolen base expectation that aligns perfectly with our organizational strategy to prioritize speed. **Carson Benge** (67.06) rounds out the top-tier plays, leveraging his leadoff position to maximize run-scoring potential against a favorable arm.\n\nWe are navigating significant volatility at the top of the order, specifically regarding **Trea Turner** (56.27) and **Kyle Schwarber** (54.53). Both are tasked with facing the formidable Chris Sale; while their raw talent keeps them in the lineup, their efficiency scores are hampered by a -19% SP skill penalty. The most difficult bench decision involved **Jerar Encarnacion**, whose 46.11 score was the highest of our non-starters. While he maintains a solid floor, the optimizer opted for **Chase Meidroth** (52.55) and **Dillon Dingler** (50.93) due to their superior situational platoon positioning. **Caleb Durbin** also fell just short of the cut (41.17); while we covet his stolen base upside, the matchup against the elite Tarik Skubal makes him a dangerous play that does not justify the risk to our game caps today.\n\nRisks remain elevated across the board, as nearly our entire starting lineup\u2014including **Victor Scott II** (59.37) and **Junior Caminero** (53.51)\u2014rests on pending confirmation of batting order. **Victor Scott II** is a high-variance play; his aggressive base-stealing mandate is suppressed by his assumed #9 spot in the order, though he remains a key pivot if lineups shift. We are closely monitoring **Pete Crow-Armstrong** (64.51), who carries strong dynamic platoon value but faces the stiff test of Freddy Peralta. We will proceed with these configurations, but managers should be prepared to pivot if late-breaking weather or lineup changes shift the viability of our marginal starters, **Gary Sanchez** and **Kazuma Okamoto**.",
